<p>Part of what is so effective about this system is that it allows the underlying text to still be readable. With most forum filters, you get a series of stars - ***** - Â that donâ€™t necessarilyÂ correspondÂ to the length of the word, which makes it difficult to understand what the poster was trying to say. Players end up frustrated by the lack of ability to communicate clearly but with the force they intended - profanity is closely tied to their emotions of whatever theyâ€™re posting about. So, when a player says â€œcoincidenceÂ is a kitten,â€ I can still get the intended meaning (and the force is undiminished), itâ€™s just much cuter.</p>

<p>Additionally, the kitten filter allows players to step back from the heated argument and intensity of the game forums. Forum posters care deeply about the issues that theyâ€™re talking about, and discussions can go from abstract to personal and insulting very fast. The humor of being called a â€œkittening motherkittenerâ€ by whoever is arguing with you about thief builds brings a sense of detachment from the insult, which seems to generally improve the quality of discussion on the forums. The comic below sums it up nicely.</p>

